ng important changes in the roles of juries and appeals, the nature of prosecution and punishment, and the pattern of growing leniency, Eldridge also shows us why this expansion occurred when it did. He concludes that the ironic combination of tumult and destabilization on the one hand, and steady growth and development on the other, made colonists more willing to criticize authority openly and officials less able to prevent it. That, in turn, established a foundation for the more celebrated flowering of colonial dissent against English authority in the eighteenth century.Steeped in primary sources and richly narrated, this is an invaluable addition to the library of anyone interested in legal history, colonial America, or the birth of free speech in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American intellectualsvBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansxColonizationzLiberiaxHistoryy19th centuryvSources. 0aAfrican AmericansxColonizationzLiberiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aPan-AfricanismxHistoryy19th centuryvSources. 0aPan-AfricanismxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aA.  aDistant.  aHeritage.  acentury.  acolonists.  acriticize.  adramatic.  aduring.  aexpansion.  aexperienced.  afreedom.  agovernment.  aoccurred.  aofficials.  aonly.  aseventeenth.  ashows.  atheir.  athis.  awhen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081472192640uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814722534.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814722534423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814722534/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBA